description: {"blocks":[{"key":"44uo8","text":"Protocol for the differentiation of human embryonic stem cells into midbrain dopaminergic neurons. This protocol recapitulates the activation of developmental pathways known to be important for mDA neuron development and mimics key sequence of events taking place in human midbrain development. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"848lc","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cddpj","text":"The protocol involves activation of not only Shh and WNT/b-catenin signaling, but also the sequential activation of additional pathways that have not been previously implemented in hESC differentiation, including: activation of non-canonical WNT signaling by WNT5A, of integrin/YAP signaling by Laminin 511, and of the nuclear receptors NR1H3 and NR1H2 by GW3965. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"e6gvk","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7j0n5","text":"In an accompanying publication (Nishimura et al., 2022; doi: 10.1016/j.stemcr.2022.10.016) single cell RNA-sequencing is used to confirm: ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8br69","text":"(i) that the cells generated in vitro follow critical developmental steps as endogenous human midbrain DA neurons in vivo, ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":29,"length":8},{"style":"italic","offset":114,"length":7}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"383ug","text":"(ii) that contaminating/inappropriate cells (from outside the ventral midbrain) are not present in the cultures, and ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a565l","text":"(iii) that the quality of the cells in vitro is comparable to that of endogenous human ventral midbrain developmental standards in vivo.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":36,"length":8},{"style":"italic","offset":128,"length":7}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dngol","text":"Additional experiments show that the neurons are functional in vitro, as assessed by electrohysiological properties and dopamine release. We conclude that this differentiation protocol models human midbrain DA neuron development in vitro. We suggest a possible application of this protocol to generate either DA progenitors for cell replacement in Parkinson's disease (PD) or DA neurons for in vitro modeling of PD and drug testing in human PD-iPS cells.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":60,"length":8},{"style":"italic","offset":229,"length":9},{"style":"italic","offset":392,"length":7}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"3445k","text":"Prior to the start of differentiation, hESCs are cultured in NutriStem® XF media on LN521 (1 ug/cm2) coated plates. Once the cells reach approximately 70-90% confluency, cells are passaged at a seeding density of 20.000 cells/cm2 with ROCK inhibitor (10 uM Y-27632), only during the first 24h.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":90,"length":1},{"style":"sup","offset":98,"length":1},{"style":"sup","offset":100,"length":1},{"style":"sup","offset":228,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6l6ts","text":"Prior to the passage of hESCs, prepare the LN521 coated plate by diluting LN521 (1 ug/cm2)  in a sufficient volume of DPBS (+/+) to completely cover the well. Incubate the plate for a minimum of 2h at 37°C or overnight at 4°C. Before seeding the cells, wash the coated plates two times with DPBS (+/+). Laminin coated plates can be wrapped in Parafilm and stored for up to two weeks at 4°C ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":88,"length":1},{"style":"sup","offset":90,"length":2}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2305d","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1tnjq","text":"To passage the hESCs, remove the media and wash the cells once with DPBS(-/-). Add pre-warmed TrypLE (100 uL/cm2) to the cells and incubate at 37°C for 4 minutes. After 4 minutes, disassociate the cells by gently pipetting up and down using a 1 mL pipette to yield a single cell solution. Inactivate the TrypLE by either adding pre-warmed defined trypsin inhibitor in a 1:1 ratio to the TrypLE or by diluting the TrypLE in a 1:5 ratio with NutriStem® XF medium with ROCK inhibitor (10 uM Y-27632). ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":111,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a1eg4","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"be634","text":"Remove a 10 uL aliquot for counting and count cells using either a hemocytometer or an automated cell counter. Determine the required volume of cell suspension needed to achieve a plating density of 20.000 cells/cm2 and then spin down the cells at 1200 rpm for 5 minutes at RT. After spinning, aspirate the medium and re-suspend the cells in NutriStem® XF with ROCK inhibitor (10 uM Y-27632) and plate the cells on pre-warmed LN521 coated plates.  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":214,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4rvee","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d1f7c","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"7f557","text":"To start the differentiation protocol, passage the hESCs onto a LN511 coated (1 ug/cm2)  plate according to the protocol outlined above . Cells are plated at a seeding density of 500.000 cells/cm2    and the media volume is approximately 1mL/cm2. In the first 11 days of the protocol it is normal and expected that the media becomes orange-yellow overnight but if it becomes completely yellow it may be good to increase the media volume slightly. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":85,"length":1},{"style":"sup","offset":87,"length":1},{"style":"sup","offset":195,"length":3},{"style":"sup","offset":199,"length":1},{"style":"sup","offset":244,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ecvr5","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c1ros","text":"The example protocol below is given for a differentiation done in a 12 well plate.  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
